Author: Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r#4741
Content: @NutellaLicka A multiple mobile wallet and exchange service. And we also have plans to build a tether for Naira on the Komodo platform.

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: @Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r very interesting, welcome to the community. Is this the private or public sector that is funding this?

Author: Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r#4741
Content: @dukeleto its private. Blockchain tech is kinda still a mystery in Nigeria. I'm most likely one of the few miners here in Nigeria.

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: @Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r you are on the bleeding edge! Very nice to hear from you. Are there any cryptocoin exchanges based in your country currently or would you be building the first?

Author: Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r#4741
Content: @dukeleto We don't have any indigenous exchange. There's Luno, they only offer BTC and ETH

Author: Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r#4741
Content: Luno is a multinational

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: @Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r sounds like you have good timing to launch a proper exchange that is geared towards your country. Are the local laws favorable towards cryptocoins?

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: @Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r also, to keep it a bit on topic, may I ask what kind of electricity rates people in your country would pay for mining? I haven't heard much statistics about Africa

Author: Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r#4741
Content: About laws. There isn't much regulation in the space right now. I guess the government is still trying to understand it all.  About electricity, its not so favourable on this front. There's no steady power supply, most times, we have to run our own generators. I'm lucky though, my mining facility has free electricity from a multinational my family leased land to. Lol. @dukeleto

Author: hyperDEX#6586
Content: haha nice

Author: Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r#4741
Content: @hyperDEX  yeah. I'm certain there aren't much miners in Nigeria because of the hassle and cost of running a farm

Author: Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r#4741
Content: I spend about $10 per month. That's cost for internet.

Author: hyperDEX#6586
Content: Wow that is pretty cool. Is solar an option for a more stable electricity?

Author: Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r#4741
Content: Nigeria is pretty hot. Solar is a solid option. That's for private individuals though. My country has really poor governance. Corruption.

Author: hyperDEX#6586
Content: The problem with solar is you would need to store it overnight too.

Author: hyperDEX#6586
Content: Batteries cost is crazy, unless you can capture that power it would be wasted effort. I saw a video once where during the day, solar panels excess power was used to pump water up to a dam. During the night, the water was released from the dam to generate hydro power and the cycle repeats.

Author: Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r#4741
Content: @hyperDEX  that's really smart.

Author: Ralphie_Alld3stroy3r#4741
Content: I can't really imagine that happening in Nigeria now. According to our government, the problem really isn't power generation. Its more of a distribution problem. This generation of leaders seriously have no interest in solving the power issues.
